There are 110 bills with the word gun in them. Five have made it to committee, and of those, two relating to concealed carry (pro carry across state lines into other CC states) and a bipartisan background bill have more support than the high capacity magazine bill does. The bill was introduced in Feb/19 and passed committee in Sep/19. It now needs to pass both the House and Senate. Since then the House has been focused on Impeachment. Before being presented to the president, it has to pass the Senate (assuming it passes the house), where is unlikely to pass. All of the 161 sponsors in the House are Dems, and there are only 47 Dems in the Senate, where they require 60 votes to pass. Based on this, Dem Senators are unlikely to force a vote that would likely fail and set the process back.

I agree with @Emil and others on this question, but I believe others are not properly incorporating the time deadline into the question. For example, a session of Congress is far longer than the 2 month period of this question which means that when you adjust for time the probability in a Congress-month is far lower. Moreover, the life of any of the bills described is far, far longer than a couple months, so you need to take that into account too.

It is useful to first consider whether such legislation has ever been passed before - and it has been, as part of the 1994 Federal Assault Weapons Ban. This substantially alters the calculus in favor of this being more likely. However, some caveats: This was a small part of a tough on crime bill that was popular with both parties, it narrowly passed by a 52-48 vote in the Senate (this Senate had more than 52 Democrats), it garnered the votes of 46 House Republicans (which is nearly unimaginable now), and was signed into law by President Clinton (a Democrat).

The US congress is in recess for most of December, its final day in session is Dec 12th. That is 111 days away, but the congress is on its summer break and wont be back until Sept 9th - there are a further three weeks were both houses are in recess, which leaves us with roughly 44 days where congress is in session (4 day weeks, 11 weeks in session - https://ballotpedia.org/116th_Congress_legislative_calendar) The average length for a bill to pass is 263 days, but the shortest time a bill can be passed by both houses is a day, for urgent bills ie finance. This wouldnt be a finance bill.
